{p id:49AEB692}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}The Ban That Wasn't: Met{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}{b}a's Failur{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}{b}e to Enforce Its Political Advertising Prohibition During the 2026 Dutch Municipal Elections{/b}{/font}
{/p}

{p id:68DFBE6E}
{font "Times New Roman"}Fabio Votta{/font}
{/p}

{p id:2294C7B8}
{font "Times New Roman"}Department of Communication Science, University of Amsterdam, The Netherlands{/font}
{/p}

{p id:66949762}
{font "Times New Roman"}Simon Kruschinski{/font}
{/p}

{p id:0311C021}
{font "Times New Roman"}GESIS -- Leibniz Institute for the Social Sciences, Mannheim, Germany{/font}
{/p}

{p id:7D7751D9}
{font "Times New Roman"}Corresponding author: Fabio Votta, f.r.votta@uva.nl{/font}
{/p}

{p id:54433B57}
{del id:20 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T14:39:25Z"}Word count:{/del}{font "Times New Roman"} ~7,000 (including tables and references){/font}
{/p}

{pagebreak}

{p id:52124736}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Abstract{/b}{/font}
{/p}

{p id:7AF60E6B}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Purpose.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} In October 2025, Meta imposed a blanket ban on political advertising across the European Union, choosing prohibition over compliance with the Transparency and Accountability of Political Advertising Re{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}gulation ({/font}{del id:25 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T14:41:13Z"}TTPA{/del}{ins id:26 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T14:41:13Z"}TTPA/PAR{/ins}{font "Times New Roman"}, Regulation EU 2024/900). This paper provides the first systematic empirical assessment of whether and how effectively Meta enforced that ban during an active election campaign: the 2026 Dutch municipal elections (Gemeenteraadsverkiezingen).{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:1 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Strong framing. Consider whether reviewers might push back on characterizing Meta's decision as 'avoidance' vs legitimate business choice. Worth preempting this objection in the discussion.
{/comment}

{p id:6E5B268D}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Method.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} We developed an automated monitoring system that collected {/font}{del id:17 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T14:39:03Z"}268,635 ads{/del}{ins id:18 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T14:39:03Z"}268,635 advertisements scraped from Meta's Ad Library{/ins}{font "Times New Roman"} from Meta&apos;s Ad Library for the Netherlands during the campaign period (February--March 2026). We classified 193,505 unique advertisers using a tw{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}o-stage process: large language model screening followed by human review. Human coders reviewed 335 accounts and 10,084 individual ads, confirming 192 accounts (57.3% of those reviewed) as political and 1,275 individual ads as containing political content.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:2 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Verify: is this the total from the Ad Library for NL during the period, or a filtered subset? The methods section should specify the exact query parameters and date range.
{/comment}

{comment id:31 by:"Editor Chen" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
TYPO: The abstract contains "scraped from Meta's Ad Library from Meta's Ad Library" — duplicate phrase. Delete one instance.
{/comment}

{p id:2E6D7975}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Findings.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} Despit{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}e the ban, 192 confirmed political accounts ran 1,329 ads on Meta&apos;s platforms, accumulating between 167,000 and 328,846 impressions and spending between EUR 100 and EUR 15,346. Meta removed only 189 of these ads ({/font}{del id:23 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T14:41:12Z"}14.2%{/del}{ins id:24 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T14:41:12Z"}14.2 percent{/ins}{font "Times New Roman"}), leaving 410 ads (30.9%) still activ{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}e at the time of analysis. Ads that were eventually removed had run for an average of {/font}{del id:21 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T14:41:12Z"}10.4 days{/del}{ins id:22 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T14:41:12Z"}10.4 calendar days{/ins}{font "Times New Roman"} (median: 7.2 days) before takedown. Enforcement was concentrated on 68 of 192 political accounts, leaving the majority of violating accounts entirely untouched.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:21 by:"Dr. Numbers" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
DATA CHECK: Only 154 of 1,329 ads (11.6%) have spend/impression data. The reported spend and impression ranges are based on fewer than 12% of confirmed political ads. This limitation is buried — it should be stated prominently alongside the numbers, not just in the Limitations section.
{/comment}

{p id:0D7D4A9A}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Implications.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} Meta's self-imposed ban produced a worse outcome for electoral transparency than compliance with the TTPA would have. Political actors who ignored the ban gained paid t{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}argeting advantages over those who complied, distorting the level playing field. The findings demonstrate that platform self-regulation through prohibition, absent meaningful enforcement, functions as regulatory avoidance rather than regulatory compliance.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:61C63485}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Keywords:{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} political advertising, platform governance, Meta, enforcement gap, electoral transparency, EU regulation{/font}
{/p}

{pagebreak}

## Introduction {id:601B5438}

{p id:78BD680A}
{font "Times New Roman"}On October 10, 2025, the European Union's Transparency and Accountability of Political Advertising Regulation ({/font}{font "Times New Roman"}TTPA, Regulation EU 2024/900) entered into force. The regulation requires platforms hosting political advertisements to label such ads clearly, disclose who paid for them, provide information about targeting techniques used, and make this information avail{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}able in searchable repositories {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(European Parliament & Council of the European Union, 2024){/font}{font "Times New Roman"}. Rather than building the infrastructure to comply with these requirements, Meta chose a different path: it banned all political advertising across the EU entirely.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:64A456F8}
{font "Times New Roman"}Meta framed this decision as a response to regulatory complexity. The company stated it could not reliably determine which ads qualified as "political" under the regulation's broad defin{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ition, which encompasses not only electoral advertisements but also issue-based advocacy {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(Meta, 2025){/font}{font "Times New Roman"}. By prohibiting all political ads, Meta avoided the obligation to build transparency mechanisms while presenting the decision as a form of overcompliance.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:34 by:"Professor Platform" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
Cite Meta's actual announcement (blog post, press release, or spokesperson quote) with a date. "Meta framed" needs attribution. If this is from the October 2025 announcement, provide a URL or reference. Platform policy scholars will check.
{/comment}

{p id:3E295C44}
{font "Times New Roman"}This {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}paper examines the consequences of that choice. Using automated monitoring data from the 2026 Dutch municipal elections (Gemeenteraadsverkiezingen, held on March 18, 2026), we document that political advertising continued on Meta's platforms despite the ba{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}n, and that Meta's enforcement of its own policy was minimal and selective. Of 1,329 ads placed by 192 confirmed political accounts, Meta removed only 189 (14.2%). The remaining ads ran freely, many accumulating thousands of impressions over days or weeks.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:5D887B0E}
{font "Times New Roman"}The empirical contribution of this paper is straightforward: it measures, for the first time, the gap between a platform's stated advertising policy and its{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} actual enforcement during an election. But the implications extend beyond measurement. Meta's ban created a regulatory outcome that is worse than either of the two scenarios it was designed to avoid. Under TTPA compliance, political ads would run with tra{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}nsparency labels and targeting disclosures. Under an effective ban, political ads would not run at all. Instead, Meta produced a third outcome: political ads run without any transparency protections, because the ban exempts them from TTPA disclosure requir{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ements while failing to prevent their publication. The result is a system in which the political actors who respect the ban are disadvantaged relative to those who ignore it, and voters receive no information about who is paying to influence their choices.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:3 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
This is the paper's core theoretical contribution. Consider foregrounding it even more prominently.
{/comment}

{comment id:24 by:"Reviewer 2" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
"For the first time" is a strong claim. Has no prior study examined enforcement gaps in platform ad bans? What about studies of Google's political ad ban in Canada (2019) or the Twitter political ad ban (2019–2023)? If this really is novel, cite the absence explicitly. If not, reframe.
{/comment}

{p id:19E4CAF4}
{font "Times New Roman"}The Dutch case is particularly instructive for several reasons. The municipal elections (Gemeenteraadsverkiezingen) involved 31 municipalities electing new councils, with hundreds of local{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} parties and candidates competing. Municipal elections in the Netherlands feature a diverse field of actors, including branches of national parties, independent local parties, and individual candidates, many of whom have limited campaign budgets and rely o{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}n affordable digital advertising to reach voters. The ban thus affected a constituency of political actors for whom alternatives to platform advertising are costly or unavailable. The topic reached the Dutch parliament on March 10, 2026, when Member of Par{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}liament Laurens Dassen (Volt) questioned Minister Heerma of the Interior (BZK) about the enforcement gap during the weekly Question Hour (Vragenuur). The case further illustrates the jurisdictional complications of EU platform regulation: Meta is headquart{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ered in Dublin and supervised by the Irish Data Protection Commission, while the Dutch media authority (Commissariaat voor de Media), designated as the national authority under the TTPA, had not yet received fine-levying powers at the time of the election.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:4 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Check: the 2026 Gemeenteraadsverkiezingen covered more than 31 municipalities. Is this the number monitored or the total? Clarify.
{/comment}

{comment id:37 by:"Reviewer International" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
Dutch municipal elections are structurally unusual: highly fragmented party systems, many hyperlocal parties, low-budget campaigns. These features may amplify the enforcement gap (many small actors harder to detect) or diminish its impact (low spend = low stakes). Discuss which direction the bias runs, so readers can calibrate transferability to national elections or other EU member states.
{/comment}

{p id:1979F8BA}
{font "Times New Roman"}This paper proceeds as follows. We first situate the problem wi{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}thin the literature on platform governance and political advertising regulation. We then describe our data collection and classification methodology. The analysis section addresses three research questions: the extent of political advertising despite the b{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}an, the patterns and effectiveness of Meta's enforcement, and the consequences for the electoral level playing field. We conclude with implications for the ongoing regulatory debate about platform self-regulation versus co-regulation in the European Union.{/font}
{/p}

## Theoretical Framework {id:40073B81}

### Platform Governance as Private Regulation {id:49B74721}

{p id:1D426B29}
{font "Times New Roman"}Digital platforms exercise regulatory power over political communication through their content mode{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ration policies, advertising rules, and algorithmic systems. {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}Gorwa {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(2019){/font}{font "Times New Roman"} conceptualized this as "platform governance," a form of private regulation in which technology companies establish and enforce rules that shape public discourse. {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}Gillespie {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(2018){/font}{font "Times New Roman"} doc{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}umented how platforms' content moderation decisions are inherently political, even when framed as neutral policy enforcement. These decisions determine what speech is amplified, what is suppressed, and what conditions apply to paid political communication.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:5 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Also consider citing Suzor (2019) 'Lawless' on the broader question of platform governance without democratic accountability.
{/comment}

{p id:03572DAF}
{font "Times New Roman"}The governance of political advertising on platforms represents a specific domain within this broader phenomenon. Platforms have adopted varying approaches over the past decade. In 2018, following the Cambridge Analytica scand{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}al, Meta introduced political ad transparency tools including an Ad Library and mandatory "paid for by" disclaimers. Google similarly implemented a political advertising transparency report. X (formerly Twitter) took a different approach in 2019, banning p{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}olitical advertising entirely under then-CEO Jack Dorsey. Each approach reflects a different model of how platforms relate to democratic processes: transparency (make ads visible), prohibition (remove ads entirely), or laissez-faire (no special treatment).{/font}
{/p}

{p id:404D3FBC}
{font "Times New Roman"}Meta's EU political ad ban represents a shift from the transparency{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} model it had championed since 2018 to the prohibition model. This shift occurred not because Meta concluded that transparency was inadequate, but because the TTPA imposed transparency requirements that Meta judged too costly to implement. The move has sig{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}nificant implications for both democratic accountability and regulatory compliance, as it removes the monitoring infrastructure that researchers, journalists, and civil society organizations had come to rely on for studying digital political communication.{/font}
{/p}

### Self-Regulation and Its Limits {id:4138EA04}

{p id:3B5BAB74}
{font "Times New Roman"}The debate between self-regulation and co-regulation in platform governance has produced a substantial body of scholarship. {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}Dommett and Power {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(2019){/font}{font "Times New Roman"} examined how platforms' self-regulatory commitments to political advertising transparency varied{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} across jurisdictions, finding significant inconsistencies in implementation. {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}Kreiss and McGregor {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(2024){/font}{font "Times New Roman"} traced how platforms' political advertising policies shifted in response to political pressure rather than principled commitments to transparency. The {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}pattern they identified, of reactive policy changes driven by reputational concerns, maps onto Meta's EU ban: a broad prohibition adopted in response to regulatory pressure, without investment in the enforcement infrastructure that would make it effective.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:66E57D39}
{font "Times New Roman"}Helberger, Pierson, and Poell {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(2018){/font}{font "Times New Roman"} argued that platforms' governing role in democratic processes requires democratic accountability mechanisms that self-regulation cannot provide. Their framework distinguishes between platforms as passive conduits, as {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}active editors, and as democratic intermediaries. A platform that bans political advertising positions itself as an editor exercising judgment about acceptable content, but without the editorial accountability that traditionally accompanies such decisions.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:21600AF9}
{font "Times New Roman"}The distinction between de jure and de {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}facto regulation is central to understanding enforcement gaps. A policy exists on paper (de jure) but may not be implemented in practice (de facto). {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}Suzor {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(2019){/font}{font "Times New Roman"} documented how platform rules are often enforced inconsistently, creating uncertainty for user{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}s and undermining the legitimacy of the regulatory system. When enforcement is selective, the policy functions not as a universal rule but as a discretionary tool that can be applied unevenly. This is particularly consequential in the domain of political a{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}dvertising, where uneven enforcement directly affects electoral competition. A rule that applies to some political actors but not others is not merely an imperfect rule; it is a rule that actively distorts the competitive environment it purports to govern.{/font}
{/p}

### The Transparency Paradox {id:2769A4C1}

{comment id:26 by:"Dr. Framing" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
This is the paper's most original theoretical contribution. Consider expanding it into a more formal framework — define the conditions under which prohibition produces less transparency than regulation. This could become the contribution reviewers remember.
{/comment}

{p id:2167D64E}
{font "Times New Roman"}The TTPA was designed to increase transparency in political advertising, not to eliminate {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}it. Article 7 requires that political ads be clearly labeled as such. Article 9 mandates disclosure of targeting techniques and, where applicable, the use of AI-generated or manipulated content. Article 11 requires platforms to maintain publicly accessible{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} advertisement repositories with political ad metadata. The regulation's logic is that political advertising is a legitimate form of political communication that should be visible and accountable {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(European Parliament & Council of the European Union, 2024){/font}{font "Times New Roman"}.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:7642A0E0}
{font "Times New Roman"}Meta's ban inverts this logic. By prohibiting political ads rather than labeling them, Meta removes them from the transparency infrastructure the TTPA was designed to create. Ads placed by political actors that evade the{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} ban do not appear in political ad repositories, do not carry transparency labels, and do not disclose targeting information. The ban thus creates a transparency deficit: the ads that do run are less visible than they would have been under TTPA compliance.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:6B582B78}
{font "Times New Roman"}This is the transparency paradox at the hea{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}rt of Meta's approach. A policy nominally stricter than the regulation produces an outcome with less transparency than the regulation requires. The paradox has a structural cause. The TTPA's transparency provisions are conditional on the existence of polit{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ical advertising: they require disclosure for ads that are classified as political. When a platform bans political advertising, the classification trigger is removed, and the transparency provisions have nothing to attach to. Ads that circumvent the ban ex{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ist in a regulatory blind spot: they are not classified as political (because the platform claims not to host political ads), and therefore they are not subject to the transparency requirements that would apply if the platform acknowledged their existence.{/font}
{/p}

### The Level Playing Field {id:5B3AEC8C}

{p id:1F5FA15E}
{font "Times New Roman"}Democratic theory assigns importance to the conditions under which political actors compete for voter support. The concept of the level playing field, while imprecise, captures the idea tha{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}t electoral competition should not be systematically skewed by advantages unrelated to the merits of competing programs {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(Dommett, 2020){/font}{font "Times New Roman"}. In the context of political advertising regulation, this means that rules should apply equally to all political actors.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:5E007D34}
{font "Times New Roman"}Selective enforcement of an advertising ban disrupts the level playing field in a specific way. Political actors who comply with the ban forgo the reach advantages of paid advertising. Those who ignore the ban, an{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}d whose ads are not removed, gain targeting capabilities that their compliant competitors lack. The distortion is compounded by the absence of transparency: because the ads do not appear in political ad libraries, voters and competing campaigns cannot see {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}who is spending money to reach them. {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}Dobber, Fathaigh, and Borgesius {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(2019){/font}{font "Times New Roman"} identified this combination of targeting power and opacity as a core concern for digital political advertising. Meta's ban, selectively enforced, produces exactly this combination.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:1DDB23B9}
{font "Times New Roman"}The level playing field concern is especially acute in municipal elections, where campaign budgets are small and marginal advantages in voter reac{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}h can determine outcomes. In national elections, parties have access to television advertising, billboards, and large-scale canvassing operations that can partially compensate for the loss of digital advertising. In municipal elections, digital advertising{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} often represents the most cost-effective channel available to small parties and independent candidates. A ban that removes this channel for compliant actors while leaving it available to non-compliant ones has a disproportionate effect at the local level.{/font}
{/p}

### Research Questions {id:66BB474A}

{p id:589B0847}
{font "Times New Roman"}We formulate three research questions to guide the empirical analysis:{/font}
{/p}

{p id:44EA1AF5}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}RQ1:{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} To what extent do political actors continue to advertise on Meta's platforms despite the platform's self-imposed ban on political advertising in the EU?{/font}
{/p}

{p id:71862ADB}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}RQ2:{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} How effectively does Meta enforce its political advertising ban, in terms of detection rates, takedown timing, and consistency across accounts?{/font}
{/p}

{p id:045BBA62}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}RQ3:{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} What consequences does selective enforcement have for electoral transparency and the level playing field?{/font}
{/p}

## Method {id:67B7EE24}

### Data Collection {id:37EA2EA8}

{p id:2E1301FC}
{font "Times New Roman"}We developed an automated monitoring system (metamonitor) that collected advertisements from Meta's Ad Library for the Netherlands betwee{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}n February 1 and March 18, 2026, covering the full campaign period for the municipal elections. The system ran continuously, executing data collection sweeps multiple times per day to capture newly placed ads and detect removals of previously observed ads.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:1E6B810F}
{font "Times New Roman"}The system combined two data collection strategies. The primary strategy queried the Meta Ad Library Graph API using both page-specific identifiers (for known political actors from candidate lists and party regi{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}strations) and keyword-based searches using 96 politically relevant Dutch-language search terms. These terms covered party names (e.g., "VVD," "GroenLinks-PvdA," "PVV"), candidate names, election-specific vocabulary (e.g., "gemeenteraadsverkiezingen," "ste{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}m op," "lijsttrekker," "kieswijzer"), and policy topics prominent in the campaign (e.g., "woningcrisis," "klimaat," "bestaanszekerheid"). The secondary strategy used browser-based scraping via headless Chromium as a fallback when API access was interrupted{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}. In total, the system collected 268,635 ads during the monitoring period. Because Meta blocks the "political and issue ads" filter for EU countries in its API, we collected all ad types and relied on the classification stage to identify political content.{/font}
{/p}

### Advertiser Classification {id:2688D92D}

{p id:6B71A2A7}
{font "Times New Roman"}We employed a two-stage classification process to identify political advertisers within the collected data.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:17 by:"Prof. Strict" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
The stats file records 40,803 unique advertisers but 193,505 total items classified. Was classification performed at the ad level or the advertiser level? If the former, "193,505 unique advertisers" is incorrect and should read "193,505 ads." Clarify.
{/comment}

{comment id:18 by:"Prof. Strict" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
What was the exact GPT-4o prompt? Reviewers will want to see it (at minimum in an appendix). Also report validation metrics: precision, recall, and F1 against a human-coded gold standard. Without these, the automated classification is a black box.
{/comment}

{p id:4F05D505}
{font "Times New Roman"}{i}Stage 1: Automated screening.{/i}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} We classified 193,505 unique adv{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ertisers using a large language model (GPT-4o), which analyzed the text content of each advertiser's ads and page metadata to determine whether the account was likely a political actor. The model was prompted to identify political parties, candidates, elec{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ted officials, political movements, and advocacy organizations engaged in electoral campaigning. It classified each advertiser as "political," "not political," or "uncertain." The model flagged 977 accounts (0.5% of all advertisers) as potentially politica{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}l. This low base rate reflects the fact that the vast majority of advertisers on Meta's platforms are commercial entities, and the keyword-based collection strategy cast a wide net that captured many non-political ads containing politically relevant terms.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:6 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Reviewers will ask: which LLM? What prompt? What was the false positive/negative rate? Consider adding a brief validation analysis or at minimum reporting the model name and classification threshold.
{/comment}

{comment id:36 by:"Dr. Ethics" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
Was ethics approval (IRB or institutional equivalent) obtained for this study? While Meta Ad Library data is publicly accessible, human coding of political actors' identities and advertising behavior may require ethics review at some institutions. State explicitly whether approval was sought and from which body.
{/comment}

{p id:0E069354}
{font "Times New Roman"}{i}Stage 2: Human review.{/i}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} Trained human coders re{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}viewed the flagged accounts and their associated ads using a custom-built web-based review tool. Coders examined the advertiser's page name, page description, ad content, and public profile to make a determination. They assessed 335 accounts and confirmed {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}192 (57.3%) as political, meaning the account belonged to a political party, candidate, political movement, or organization directly engaged in campaigning for the municipal elections. The remaining 143 accounts (42.7%) were classified as non-political, in{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}cluding news organizations reporting on the elections, commercial advertisers using political keywords in their ad copy, and non-governmental organizations with no direct electoral engagement. In addition, coders reviewed 10,084 individual ads from politic{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}al and borderline accounts and confirmed 1,275 (12.6%) as containing explicitly political content, defined as electoral appeals, candidate promotions, party branding in the context of the elections, or issue advocacy directly tied to electoral competition.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:7 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
How were these 335 selected from the 977 AI-flagged accounts? Random sample? Purposive? Top-N by ad count? This is a potential selection bias that needs explicit justification.
{/comment}

{comment id:8 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Report intercoder reliability if multiple coders annotated the same items. If single-coder, acknowledge this as a limitation.
{/comment}

{comment id:19 by:"Prof. Strict" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
How many coders? Was intercoder reliability (ICR) computed? If multiple coders, report Krippendorff's alpha. If a single coder, acknowledge this as a limitation. "Trained human coders" without ICR will draw a major revision request from any methods-oriented reviewer.
{/comment}

### Operational Definitions {id:374C36EC}

{p id:315F1510}
{font "Times New Roman"}We defined a "political ad{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}vertiser" as any account that self-identified as a political party, candidate, or political movement, or that placed ads with explicit electoral content (calls to vote, candidate endorsements, party branding in the context of the elections). This definitio{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}n is intentionally narrower than the TTPA's definition of political advertising, which includes issue-based advocacy without explicit electoral content. Our figures therefore represent a conservative lower bound on the true volume of political advertising.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:0A550818}
{font "Times New Roman"}We defined "takedown" as the removal of an ad by {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}Meta during the monitoring period, detected through comparison of successive data collection sweeps. An ad was classified as "taken down" if it appeared in an earlier collection sweep but was absent from subsequent sweeps while its account remained active.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:20 by:"Prof. Strict" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
What was the sweep interval? If sweeps ran every 6 hours vs every 24 hours, the takedown timing estimates change substantially. Report the median sweep interval.
{/comment}

### Monitoring Takedowns {id:6FDAC6A9}

{p id:7AE5023A}
{font "Times New Roman"}The monitoring system collected data in repeated sweeps, allowing us to track the lifecycle of individual ads through their unique ad archive identifiers. By comparing ad presenc{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}e across sweeps, we identified three categories: ads that were removed (taken down by Meta, identified by disappearance from the Ad Library while the parent account and other ads remained visible), ads that remained active at the end of the monitoring peri{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}od, and ads that became inactive for other reasons (campaign end, budget exhaustion, or advertiser-initiated pauses). For ads that were taken down, we calculated the duration between first observation and last observation as a proxy for time-to-takedown. T{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}his proxy likely underestimates true ad duration, because an ad may have been placed before our first observation of it. A dedicated takedown log recorded each detected removal event with timestamps, enabling the temporal analysis reported in the findings.{/font}
{/p}

### Limitations {id:29588401}

{p id:2E3886FB}
{font "Times New Roman"}Several limitations should be noted. First, our system could only observe ads that appeared in Meta's Ad Library. Ads that were placed and removed before our monitoring sweeps would not be captured, meaning our figures undercount both the to{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}tal volume of political advertising and the total number of takedowns. Second, the distinction between Meta-initiated takedowns and advertiser-initiated ad pauses or removals is not always clear from the data. We classify an ad as taken down only when the {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}pattern is consistent with platform enforcement (ad removed while other ads from the same account remain active), but some misclassification is possible. Third, our classification of political accounts and ads relied on human judgment, and we cannot rule o{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ut that some political accounts were missed by the automated screening stage. Fourth, spend and impression data from the Meta Ad Library are reported in ranges rather than exact figures, introducing imprecision in our estimates of total spending and reach.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:25 by:"Reviewer 2" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
This is a fundamental threat to validity that the paper underplays. If Meta's enforcement is actually fast (removing ads within hours), your system would systematically miss successful enforcement actions, making Meta look worse than it is. Can you bound this? E.g., what fraction of your sweep intervals were <6 hours?
{/comment}

{figure id:08689503 rId:rId9 src:"word/media/image1.png" width:5943600emu height:3714750emu}
{/figure}

{p id:7E50408D}
