## Analysis {id:45FB94B0}

### RQ1: Political Advertising Despite the Ban {id:1797F2AC}

{p id:390363D6}
{font "Times New Roman"}Despite Meta's prohibition on political advertising, we confirmed 192 accounts as political advertisers that placed a total of 1,329 ads during the campaign period. These accounts represented a range of{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} political actors, from local parties and individual candidates to national advocacy organizations and political movements. To put this in context: the automated screening flagged 977 of 193,505 unique advertisers (0.5%) as potentially political, and human{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} reviewers confirmed 192 of 335 reviewed accounts (57.3%) as genuinely political. The 192 confirmed accounts represent a conservative lower bound, as the remaining 642 flagged accounts that were not reviewed likely include additional political advertisers.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:66C1B290}
{font "Times New Roman"}Table 1 pr{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}esents the most active political advertisers by ad volume. The leading advertiser was PAX, a peace organization, with 117 ads (8.8% of all confirmed political ads). Wakker Emmen, a local party in the municipality of Emmen, placed 82 ads (6.2%). DURF, a loc{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}al political movement, placed 63 ads (4.7%). Toekomstig KLM placed 38 ads (2.9%). The distribution was heavily skewed: the top four accounts were responsible for 300 of 1,329 ads (22.6%), while many of the remaining 188 accounts placed only one or two ads.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:9 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
PAX is a peace organization, not a political party. Clarify the operational definition: are advocacy organizations included alongside parties and candidates? This affects the claim about 'political advertising.'
{/comment}

