{p id:1484C398}
{font "Times New Roman"}The total spend across all confirmed political ads ranged from EUR 100 to EUR 15,346 (Meta reports spend in ranges rather than exact figures). Total impressions ranged from 167,000 to 328,8{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}46. While these figures are modest compared to national election campaigns, they are significant in the context of Dutch municipal elections. In municipalities with 30,000 to 80,000 eligible voters, even modest ad budgets can reach a substantial fraction o{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}f the electorate. A single ad with 5,000 impressions in a municipality of 50,000 residents reaches the equivalent of 10% of the local electorate, a margin that can matter in council elections where seats are allocated proportionally and thresholds are low.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:10 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
This is the Ad Library's reported range (lower/upper bounds). Note that Meta's spend reporting in the Ad Library uses broad ranges and may underestimate actual expenditure.
{/comment}

{comment id:23 by:"Reviewer 2" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
EUR 100–EUR 15,346 total spend across an entire election is, frankly, negligible. The paper needs to do more work justifying why this matters. Compare to typical municipal campaign budgets. If a candidate spends EUR 50 on a Meta ad, is that really a "level playing field" problem? The normative weight of the argument outstrips the empirical evidence.
{/comment}

{p id:5B753A3C}
{font "Times New Roman"}Ads were distributed across Meta's platform ecosystem. The majority appeared on Facebook, with{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} additional placements on Instagram, Messenger, and the Audience Network (see Figure 1). This multi-platform distribution indicates that political advertisers were using Meta's standard ad placement tools, which automatically distribute ads across platform{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}s for maximum reach, rather than narrowly targeting a single platform. The cross-platform placement also means that the ads reached users who may not have encountered them on Facebook alone, extending the reach of political messaging beyond any single app.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:32 by:"Editor Chen" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
Figure cross-references may be misaligned. The text references "Figure 1" and "Figure 2" for different content than the figure captions suggest. Verify all 10 figure references match their captions after any reordering.
{/comment}

{p id:131845B9}
{font "Times New Roman"}The temporal distribution of ads across the campaign period reveals sustained advertising activity, with clear increases in volume duri{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ng the final two weeks before election day (see Figure 2). This pattern is consistent with strategic campaign advertising rather than accidental or one-off placements. Political actors were using Meta's advertising tools deliberately and continuously, adju{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}sting their spending to peak when voter attention was highest. The sustained nature of the activity also suggests that advertisers learned over the course of the campaign that enforcement was unlikely, reinforcing their willingness to continue placing ads.{/font}
{/p}

