{/p}

### RQ2: Enforcement Patterns {id:51040583}

{p id:6C5A4E2C}
{font "Times New Roman"}Meta's enforcement of its own ban was limited in scope, slow in execution, and inconsistent across accounts.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:69093BA8}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Detection and removal rates.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} Of 1,329 confirmed political ads, Meta removed 189 (14.2%). At the time of analysis, 410 ads (30.9%) remained active on the platform, and 730 ads (54.9%) were inactive for other{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} reasons, a category that includes ads whose budget was exhausted, ads that the advertiser paused or ended, and ads that may have been removed by Meta outside our detection window. The 189 confirmed takedowns represent cases where removal was clearly platf{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}orm-initiated, identified through disappearance from the Ad Library while other ads from the same account remained visible. The 14.2% takedown rate means that for every political ad Meta removed, approximately six political ads continued running unimpeded.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:11 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Key finding. But consider the counterfactual: what is Meta's takedown rate for other policy violations? Without a baseline, 14.2% is hard to interpret as 'low.' Even a rough comparison would strengthen the argument.
{/comment}

