{p id:68C73F66}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Takedown timing.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} For the 189 ads that Meta did remove, the average time from first observation to removal was{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} 10.4 days, with a median of 7.2 days (see Figure 3). The distribution of takedown times was right-skewed: some ads were removed within days, while others ran for two or three weeks before action was taken. Given that the entire campaign period lasted appr{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}oximately seven weeks, a median takedown time of one week means that removed ads had already completed a substantial portion of their intended campaign run before enforcement occurred. In municipal elections, where the formal campaign period is short and v{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}oter attention peaks in the final days, a week of unimpeded advertising represents a significant share of the campaign window. Many of the ads that were eventually removed had likely already delivered most of their intended impressions before the takedown.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:12 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Given the campaign period was roughly 30-45 days, an average ad running 10.4 days before takedown means it was live for 25-35% of the entire campaign. Worth making this point explicit.
{/comment}

{p id:686B7307}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Account-level selectivity.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} Enforcement was concentrated on a minority of political accounts. Of the 192 confirmed political accounts, Meta took enforcement action against only 68 (35.4%). The remaining 124 accounts (64.6%) placed politica{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}l ads that were never removed during the entire monitoring period. Among the 68 accounts that did experience enforcement, the intensity varied: some had all their ads removed, while others had only a subset taken down, with remaining ads left active. This {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}inconsistency within accounts further suggests that Meta's detection was ad-level rather than account-level, meaning the platform did not flag entire accounts as political advertisers even after identifying individual ads from those accounts as violations.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:22 by:"Dr. Numbers" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
DATA DISCREPANCY: The enforcement stats file shows 198 total political accounts (126 no takedowns + 62 partial + 10 all removed = 198), but the manuscript reports 192 accounts (68 + 124 = 192). Where did the 6-account difference go? Reconcile these numbers or explain the filtering.
{/comment}

