{p id:4A3DE85F}
{font "Times New Roman"}The selectivity of enforcement raises questions about what triggers Meta's detection mechanisms. If enforcement is primarily report-based, then the ban functions as a complaint-driven system {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}rather than a proactive policy. This interpretation is consistent with the observed pattern: accounts that attracted attention, through user complaints, media coverage, or competitor reports, were subject to enforcement, while accounts that operated withou{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}t drawing attention were left untouched. The implication is that Meta did not invest in proactive detection systems for political advertising violations, relying instead on external signals that are inherently partial and biased toward more visible actors.{/font}
{/p}

