### RQ3: Level Playing Field and Transparency Implications {id:1DF373DC}

{p id:5E6F2513}
{font "Times New Roman"}The combination of a nominally strict ban, minimal enforcement, and absent transparency protections produces several distortions relevant to electoral fairness.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:74DDD26E}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Asymmetric advantages.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} Political actors who complied with Meta's ban, by refraining from placing paid advertisements, forfeited the reach and targeting capabilities that paid advertising provides. Those who ignored the ban gained access to{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} Meta's full advertising toolkit, including demographic targeting, geographic targeting, interest-based targeting, and lookalike audience expansion, without the transparency disclosures that the TTPA was designed to require. This asymmetry rewards non-comp{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}liance and punishes compliance. Consider the concrete case of Wakker Emmen, which placed 82 ads during the campaign period. A competing local party in Emmen that respected the ban had access only to organic posting, which reaches a small and unpredictable {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}fraction of a page's followers due to algorithmic filtering. The party that paid for advertising could target specific demographics in specific neighborhoods; the party that followed the rules could not. The competitive distortion is direct and measurable.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:13 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Consider adding a concrete example: e.g., Party X ran 80 ads reaching Y thousand voters while Party Z, which complied with the ban, reached zero through paid channels.
{/comment}

{p id:3AAB3020}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Transparency deficit.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} Under the TTPA framework, political ads would appear in Meta's political advertising repository with information about the sponsoring entit{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}y, the amount spent, the audience reached, and the targeting criteria used. Under Meta's ban, none of this information is available. The ads placed by political actors do not carry political advertising labels, do not appear in political ad repositories, a{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}nd do not disclose targeting parameters. Voters encountering these ads have no way to identify them as paid political communication. The ban thus produces a transparency outcome that is strictly worse than the regulatory framework it was designed to avoid.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:2A5982C8}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Jurisdictional fragmentation.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} The enforcement difficulties are compounded by jurisdictional complexity. Meta's European headquarters is in Dublin, placing it under the supervision of the Irish Data Protection Commission for GDPR purposes and the Irish media {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}regulator for certain DSA obligations. The Dutch Commissariaat voor de Media was designated as the national authority responsible for political advertising transparency under the TTPA, but at the time of the 2026 elections, it had not yet received the powe{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}r to levy fines for violations. This jurisdictional gap meant that even if the Dutch authority had wished to compel Meta to enforce its ban more effectively or to comply with TTPA transparency requirements instead, it lacked the enforcement tools to do so.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:30 by:"Commissioner Torres" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
Under the TTPA, the designated national authority for the Netherlands would enforce political ad transparency. But Meta's ban means there are no "political ads" to regulate — the Commissariaat can't enforce transparency obligations on ads that officially don't exist. Make this Catch-22 more explicit; it's a powerful regulatory argument.
{/comment}

{p id:507E7181}
{font "Times New Roman"}The contrast with the Digital Services Act enforcement timeline is instructive. In December 2025, the Europ{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ean Commission imposed a EUR 120 million fine on X (formerly Twitter) for violations of the DSA's transparency requirements, the first major enforcement action under the regulation {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(European Commission, 2025){/font}{font "Times New Roman"}. This action demonstrated that EU regulators ar{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}e willing to use their enforcement powers against major platforms. Yet the political advertising domain remained untouched, in part because the institutional infrastructure for TTPA enforcement was still being assembled when the Dutch elections took place.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:29 by:"Commissioner Torres" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
Verify the EUR 120 million figure and the date (December 2025). If this refers to the DSA non-compliance fine, confirm the exact legal basis (DSA Art. 56?). Regulatory citations must be precise — an incorrect fine amount would undermine credibility with policy readers.
{/comment}

{p id:56535758}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Parliamentary response.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} The enforcement gap attracted political attention within the Netherlands. On March 10, 2026, during the weekly Questio{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}n Hour (Vragenuur) of the Dutch House of Representatives, Member of Parliament Laurens Dassen (Volt) questioned Minister Heerma of the Interior (BZK) about Meta's failure to enforce its political advertising ban and the implications for the municipal elect{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ions. The parliamentary exchange exposed the regulatory impasse from the perspective of a national government. Minister Heerma could acknowledge the problem but could not offer a remedy, because enforcement authority over Meta lies with Irish regulators (u{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}nder the country-of-origin principle) and the European Commission (under the DSA's centralized supervision of very large online platforms). This parliamentary intervention illustrates both the political salience of the issue and its structural intractabili{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ty under the current regulatory architecture. National legislators can raise the problem, media can report on it, and researchers can document it, but none of these actors can compel a platform headquartered in another member state to change its practices.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:567DA3A0}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}The accountability vacuum.{/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} The jurisdictional fragmentation creates what amounts to an accountability vacuum for political advertising enforcement. The Dutch C{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ommissariaat voor de Media, designated as the national authority for political advertising transparency under the TTPA, had not yet received fine-levying powers. The Irish media regulator, which has supervisory jurisdiction over Meta, has no direct stake i{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}n Dutch municipal elections. The European Commission, which fined X EUR 120 million under the DSA in December 2025 {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(European Commission, 2025){/font}{font "Times New Roman"}, has not yet brought enforcement actions related to the TTPA. The result is that no authority with both the juris{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}diction and the enforcement tools took action on Meta's political advertising in the Netherlands during the 2026 elections. This is not an oversight; it is a structural feature of the EU's multi-layered regulatory framework during its implementation phase.{/font}
{/p}

{figure id:536C3163 rId:rId16 src:"word/media/image8.png" width:5943600emu height:2971800emu}
{/figure}

{p id:785A4DBE}
{font "Times New Roman"}{b}Figure 8. {/b}{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}{i}Distribution of political ads by actor type (parties, candidates, movements, advocacy organizations).{/i}{/font}
{/p}

{figure id:09F3BFA4 rId:rId17 src:"word/media/image9.png" width:5943600emu height:2971800emu}
{/figure}

