{/p}

{comment id:33 by:"Editor Chen" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
10 figures in a ~7,000 word paper is high for most journals. Consider whether Figures 8–10 (actor type breakdowns) could be consolidated into a single multi-panel figure or moved to an online appendix. Prioritize figures that directly answer the RQs.
{/comment}

## Discussion {id:7A19C206}

{p id:11266821}
{font "Times New Roman"}The findings from the 2026 Dutch municipal elections document a specific failure mode of platform self-regulation: a prohibition that is announced but not enforced, creating outcomes worse than either effective prohibition or regulated permission.{/font}
{/p}

### The Enforcement Gap as Regulatory Avoidance {id:3855DEA6}

{p id:61E48391}
{font "Times New Roman"}Meta's political advertising ban can be understood as a form of regulatory avoidance rather than regulatory compliance. The TTPA requires platforms that host political advertising to invest in label{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ing systems, transparency databases, and targeting disclosure mechanisms. By banning political advertising, Meta avoided these investments. But the ban also required enforcement investment, detection systems, content review capacity, and takedown infrastru{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}cture, that Meta evidently did not make. The result is a policy that serves Meta's regulatory positioning (it can claim to have gone further than the regulation requires) while failing to produce the outcomes that either the ban or the regulation intended.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:14 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
This is a strong claim. Ensure the evidence supports characterizing it as deliberate avoidance rather than implementation difficulty. The Vragenuur transcript shows Meta told the government they found the regulation 'onduidelijk' (unclear).
{/comment}

{comment id:27 by:"Dr. Framing" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
"Regulatory avoidance" implies intentionality. The evidence is consistent with this interpretation but also with organizational incapacity (Meta genuinely couldn't classify political ads at scale). The paper should acknowledge both possibilities and explain why the distinction matters for policy — avoidance warrants penalties, incapacity warrants technical standards.
{/comment}

{p id:318CF4D0}
{font "Times New Roman"}This pattern echoes findings from other domains of platform governance. {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}Suzor {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(2019){/font}{font "Times New Roman"} documented how platforms often adopt broad rules that they lack the capacity or willingness to enforce consistently. The politic{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}al advertising ban fits this pattern. The breadth of the prohibition, covering all political advertising under a broad definition, makes consistent enforcement operationally challenging. But the 14.2% takedown rate and the concentration of enforcement on 3{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}5.4% of accounts suggest that the challenge is not merely operational. It reflects a policy design in which enforcement is secondary to the announcement of the policy itself. Meta's incentive structure clarifies the dynamic: the company earns revenue from {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}every ad placed on its platform, including those placed by political actors in violation of the ban. Proactive enforcement of the ban would require Meta to invest resources in order to reduce its own revenue, a combination that market logic does not favor.{/font}
{/p}

### Implications for the Self-Regulation Debate {id:45FB3B2B}

{p id:3FAA0797}
{font "Times New Roman"}The findings contribu{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}te to the ongoing debate about the effectiveness of platform self-regulation in the domain of political communication. Proponents of self-regulation argue that platforms are best positioned to develop and enforce rules tailored to their technical capabilit{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ies and user communities {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(Flew, Martin, & Suzor, 2019){/font}{font "Times New Roman"}. Critics argue that platforms' commercial incentives are misaligned with democratic accountability, and that meaningful regulation requires external enforcement {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}(Helberger, Pierson, & Poell, 2018){/font}{font "Times New Roman"}.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:28 by:"Dr. Framing" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
The paper's structure is predominantly empirical-descriptive. Consider whether you can articulate a more explicit theoretical mechanism: WHY does enforcement fail? Is it capacity (can't detect), willingness (won't enforce), or design (ban is structured to fail)? Even a brief typology would strengthen the contribution beyond documentation.
{/comment}

{p id:2E01B9A8}
{font "Times New Roman"}The Dutch case supports the critics. Meta's ban was a self-regulat{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ory choice. It was not required by the TTPA, which envisions transparency rather than prohibition. Meta chose prohibition over compliance because prohibition is cheaper: it requires no new transparency infrastructure. But the choice to prohibit without enf{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}orcing produces a regulatory vacuum. Political ads run without transparency labels, without repository listings, and without targeting disclosures. The self-regulatory choice did not just fail to achieve the regulation's goals; it actively undermined them.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:7D3A73D9}
{font "Times New Roman"}This finding has implications for the broader EU regulatory framework. The DSA requires{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} very large online platforms to conduct systemic risk assessments (Articles 34-35) and to take proportionate mitigation measures for risks to democratic processes. Article 39 specifically requires that ad repositories be maintained with information about a{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ll advertisements served on the platform. An advertising ban that is not enforced, and that creates transparency deficits for electoral processes, may itself constitute a systemic risk that Meta is required to assess and mitigate under the DSA. The interac{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}tion between the TTPA and the DSA creates overlapping regulatory expectations that Meta's current approach does not meet. Under the TTPA, Meta avoids transparency obligations by claiming it does not host political ads. Under the DSA, Meta is required to ma{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}intain ad repositories and assess electoral risks regardless of its advertising policies. The two regulations, read together, leave little room for the position that banning political ads while failing to enforce the ban satisfies a platform's obligations.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:651EEC6C}
{font "Times New Roman"}The Dutch case also{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} illustrates the temporal dimension of regulatory failure. The TTPA entered into force in October 2025. The Dutch municipal elections took place in March 2026, five months later. In that five-month window, the Dutch national authority had not yet received {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}enforcement powers, the European Commission had not yet addressed TTPA violations, and Meta had not built enforcement infrastructure for its own ban. The election proceeded in what amounted to a regulatory interregnum: the old system (Meta's voluntary tran{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}sparency tools) had been dismantled, and the new system (TTPA-mandated transparency) had not yet been implemented. This timing gap is not unique to the Netherlands. Any EU election held during the early implementation phase of the TTPA faces the same risk.{/font}
{/p}

### Limitations and Future Research {id:1EA76B0D}

{p id:871E03A2}
{font "Times New Roman"}Preliminary evidence suggests that Google's ad infrastructure also served political ads during the Dutch municipal elections despite a similar ban, indicating that the enforcement gap may extend beyond a single platform.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:35 by:"Professor Platform" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
Google's parallel ban is mentioned only in the limitations. Given that Google Ads also served political content during the same election, this deserves more than a footnote — even a brief paragraph comparing the two platforms' approaches would significantly strengthen the paper's implications.
{/comment}

{p id:53418651}
{font "Times New Roman"}This study has several limitations that future research should address. First, our monitoring captured only ads visible i{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}n Meta's Ad Library; ads removed before our collection sweeps were missed. The true volume of political advertising, and the true number of takedowns, is likely higher than our figures indicate. Second, our study covers a single election in a single countr{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}y. While the Dutch municipal elections provide a useful case, the generalizability of findings to other EU member states, other election types, and other time periods remains to be established. Third, we could not determine with certainty the mechanisms be{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}hind Meta's enforcement decisions: whether takedowns were triggered by user reports, automated detection, or some combination. Understanding these mechanisms would require access to Meta's internal processes, which is not available to external researchers.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:314899F9}
{font "Times New Roman"}Future research should extend this m{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}onitoring approach to other EU elections to assess whether the enforcement patterns we document are consistent across contexts. The German state elections in Baden-Wurttemberg (2026) and the anticipated European Parliament elections provide natural compari{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}son cases. Comparative studies across member states would illuminate whether jurisdictional factors, the size of the election, or the political salience of the campaign affect enforcement rates. Research should also examine whether the TTPA's transparency {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}requirements, once fully implemented with national enforcement powers, produce better outcomes than Meta's current prohibition approach. The planned implementation of enforcement capacities across EU member states creates a natural experiment: elections he{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ld before national authorities have enforcement powers can be compared with elections held after. Finally, the question of how selective enforcement affects voter information and electoral outcomes deserves sustained empirical attention, including survey-b{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ased research that measures voter awareness of paid political content on platforms operating under advertising bans, and field experiments that assess whether voters can distinguish paid from organic political content in the absence of transparency labels.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:38 by:"Reviewer International" date:"2026-03-24T10:00:00Z"}
The German Baden-Württemberg and Israeli elections are already being monitored by your system (per the methods section context). Can you include even preliminary cross-national comparisons? Even a footnote saying "preliminary data from BW26 shows a similar pattern" would dramatically strengthen the generalizability claim.
{/comment}

## Conclusion {id:6474F30C}

{p id:68B9C57B}
{font "Times New Roman"}Meta's political advertising ban in the European Union was presented as a decisive response to regulatory requirements. Our analysis of the 2026 Dutch{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} municipal elections reveals it to be something else: a policy that is announced rather than enforced, that avoids regulatory compliance rather than exceeding it, and that produces worse transparency outcomes than the regulation it was designed to preempt.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:74859AF0}
{font "Times New Roman"}The numbers tell a clear story. Of 1,329 confirmed political ads from 192 accounts, Meta removed 189 (14.2%). The remaining 86% of known political ads were either still active or h{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ad completed their runs without enforcement action. Ads that were eventually removed ran for a median of 7.2 days before takedown. Enforcement reached only 68 of 192 political accounts (35.4%), leaving the majority of violating accounts entirely untouched.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:18302F08}
{font "Times New Roman"}These findings have three principal implicat{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}ions. First, platform self-regulation through prohibition does not work when the prohibiting platform lacks the enforcement infrastructure, or the enforcement incentive, to make the prohibition effective. A ban without enforcement is not a ban; it is a pol{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}icy statement. Second, Meta's approach produces a transparency outcome strictly worse than TTPA compliance. Under the TTPA, political ads would run with labels, disclosures, and repository listings. Under Meta's unenforced ban, they run with none of these.{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} Third, selective enforcement distorts the electoral level playing field by rewarding non-compliance. Political actors who respect the ban lose access to paid advertising. Those who ignore it gain paid targeting advantages without transparency obligations.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:6B367B0F}
{font "Times New Roman"}The policy implications are direct. Co-regulation, in which public authorities set standards and retain enforcement powers{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}, is necessary to prevent platforms from substituting self-serving policy announcements for meaningful compliance. The TTPA was designed for transparency, not for bans. Meta's response, replacing transparency requirements with an unenforced prohibition, ci{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}rcumvents the regulation's intent. As EU member states build out their national enforcement capacities under the TTPA, they should treat platform advertising bans not as a form of overcompliance but as a potential form of regulatory avoidance that requires{/font}{font "Times New Roman"} scrutiny. Regulators should consider whether a platform that bans political advertising but fails to enforce the ban is in compliance with its obligations under the DSA's systemic risk provisions, which require mitigation of risks to democratic processes.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:51F9CB45}
{font "Times New Roman"}For researchers, the case demonstrates both the feasibility and the necessity of independent mo{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}nitoring. The enforcement gap we document was invisible until an external monitoring system made it measurable. Meta's own reporting provided no indication that political ads were running in violation of its ban. Without independent data collection, the ga{/font}{font "Times New Roman"}p between policy and practice would have remained hidden. This highlights the importance of maintaining research access to platform advertising data, an access that is itself threatened by Meta's restrictions on the Ad Library API for EU political content.{/font}
{/p}

{p id:140E045D}
{font "Times New Roman"}The 2026 Dutch municipal elections are one case in a large and evolving regulatory context. But they demonstrate a principle with broad application: when a platform announces a rule it does not enforce, {/font}{font "Times New Roman"}the result is not regulation. It is the appearance of regulation. And the appearance of regulation may be worse than no regulation at all, because it removes the pressure to develop meaningful alternatives while leaving the underlying problems unaddressed.{/font}
{/p}

{comment id:15 by:"Mira" date:"2026-03-18T11:15:00Z"}
Consider ending with a forward-looking statement about the AI Act Art. 50 transparency obligations taking effect August 2026, and whether the same enforcement gap will repeat.
{/comment}

